ty's public markets to the political economy of the city from the restoration of the Republic in 1867 to the heyday of the Mexican miracle and the PRI in the 1960s. Each day vendors interacted with customers, suppliers, government officials, and politicians, and the multiple conflicts that arose repeatedly tested the institutional capacity of the state. Through a close reading of the archives and an analysis of vendors' intersecting economic and political lives, Ingrid Bleynat explores the dynamics, as well as the limits, of capitalist development in Mexico.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCapitalismxHistoryzMexicozMexico City. 0aCapitalism-Mexico-Mexico City-History. 0aMarketsxGovernment policyxHistoryzMexicozMexico City. 0aMarketsxHistoryzMexicozMexico City. 0aMarkets-Government policy-Mexico-Mexico City-History. 0aMarkets-Mexico-Mexico City-History. 0aMexico City (Mexico)-Economic conditions-19th century. 0aMexico City (Mexico)-Economic conditions-20th century. 0aVending standsxGovernment policyxHistoryzMexicozMexico City. 0aVending standsxHistoryzMexicozMexico City. 0aVending stands-Government policy-Mexico-Mexico City-History. 0aVending stands-Mexico-Mexico City-History. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh  aConfederación Nacional de Organizaciones Populares.  aMexican miracle.  aMexico.  aPartido Revolucionario Institucional.  acapitalism.  adevelopmentalism.  amarket vendors.  aproprietary mode of production.  apublic markets.  aurban politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08